#Dollar

Reading and regulating the format of the dollar data and controlling the data types:

dolar <- read_excel("dolar.xlsx")
names(dolar) = c("date", "dolar_value")
dolar <- as.data.table(dolar[2:2945,1:2])
dolar$date <- format(as.Date(dolar$date, format = "%d/%m/%Y"), "%Y-%m-%d")
dolar$date <- as.Date(dolar$date)
str(dolar)
## Classes 'data.table' and 'data.frame':   2944 obs. of  2 variables:
##  $ date       : Date, format: "2010-01-04" "2010-01-05" ...
##  $ dolar_value: num  1.49 1.48 1.47 1.47 1.47 ...
##  - attr(*, ".internal.selfref")=<externalptr>

Plotting dollar rates and the fitting line:

ggplot(dolar, aes(x=date, y=dolar_value)) +
  geom_line() + 
  xlab("") + scale_x_date(date_breaks = "3 month", date_labels = "%m/%y") + stat_smooth() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(size = 18)) +  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45)) +
    xlab("Date") + ylab("Dollar Rate") + theme(axis.title.x = element_text(size = 25)) + theme(axis.title.y=element_text(size = 25)) 
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'gam' and formula 'y ~ s(x, bs = "cs")'

We can examine the dollar data: +Overall we can see an increasing trend in dollar rates and the increase is sharpening in the last two years as we can see from the fitting line. +There is no observable monthly or quarterly effect as dollar exchange rates does not depend on season or the month but depends on the economic decisions and policies on both side government. However, we observe a trend on the extreme points of the graph +The first abnormality on 09.18 which is the date when the president of TCMB is changed suddenly and it creates an insecure enviroment for Turkish currency. Another abnormability is again happening

The Correlation between Euro and Dollar

euro_dolar <- dolar[,Euro:=euro$euro_value]
cor(euro_dolar$Euro , euro_dolar$dolar_value,  method = "pearson", use = "complete.obs")
## [1] 0.9937468

The correllation is extremely high.

par(mar = c(4, 4, .1, .1))
